      "content": "Vector addition is straightforward — you add the corresponding components. For vectors a and b, you add the first elements together, then the second, then the third."
    },
    { "role": "USER", "content": "ok so for a+b I get [-1, 5, -1]?" },
    {
      "role": "ASSISTANT",
      "content": "Exactly right! a+b = [-1, 5, -1]. Well done."
    },
    {
      "role": "USER",
      "content": "and b+a should be the same because of commutativity?"
    },
    {
      "role": "ASSISTANT",
      "content": "Correct — vector addition is commutative, so b+a = a+b = [-1, 5, -1]."
    },
    {
      "role": "USER",
      "content": "I submitted both and got the first one right but the second one wrong, I put [-1, 5, 1] by mistake"
    },
    {
      "role": "ASSISTANT",
      "content": "That's just a sign error on the last component — easy to do. The last element of a is 3 and of b is -4, so their sum is -1, not 1."
    },
    {
      "role": "USER",
      "content": "got it. now I'm stuck on part b, what does 3c mean?"
    },
    {
      "role": "ASSISTANT",
      "content": "Scalar multiplication — you multiply every component of c by 3. So 3c = [3×0, 3×4, 3×(-1)] = [0, 12, -3]."
    },
